{{Short description|American painter}} '''Beulah Eisle Stevenson''' (1890–1965) was an [[United States|American]] painter and printmaker.
Born in [[Brooklyn Heights]], Stevenson lived there her entire life. In New York she studied at the [[Pratt Institute]] and the [[Art Students League of New York|Art Students League]], where her instructors included [[John French Sloan|John Sloan]]; in [[Provincetown, Massachusetts|Provincetown]], she worked with [[Hans Hofmann]]. Her work appeared in many group shows, and she won a number of awards.<ref name="PeopleReading">{{cite book|title=People Reading: Selections from the Collection of Donald and Patricia Oresman|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XYG6tgAACAAJ|year=2008|publisher=Spartanburg Art Museum}}</ref> She was a curator at the [[Brooklyn Museum]] for many years,<ref name="peytonwright.com">{{cite web|url=http://peytonwright.com/modern/artists/beulah-stevenson/|title=Beulah Stevenson – Peyton Wright Gallery|publisher=|accessdate=29 October 2017}}</ref> and that museum owns a number of examples of her work,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/artists/4699/objects|title=Brooklyn Museum|website=www.brooklynmuseum.org|accessdate=29 October 2017}}</ref> as do the [[Library of Congress]] and the [[New York Public Library]].<ref name="PeopleReading"/> Stevenson maintained many professional associations during her career; she was president of the [[New York Society of Women Artists]], a board member of the [[National Association of Women Artists]], and a vice-president of the [[Brooklyn Society of Artists]]. She also belonged to the [[American Artists' Congress]]; when that organization came to become closer in affiliation to the [[communism|Communist Party]], she left to join the [[Federation of Modern Painters and Sculptors]].<ref name="peytonwright.com"/> Stevenson was said by a friend to have destroyed many of her papers prior to her death, but a collection was donated to the [[Archives of American Art]] at the [[Smithsonian Institution]] and has been partially digitized.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/beulah-e-stevenson-papers-10106 |title=Beulah E. Stevenson papers, 1928–1966 &#124; Archives of American Art |publisher=Aaa.si.edu |date= |accessdate=2017-10-29}}</ref>
